es between both independent states in the 1960s, yet the British government initially interpreted these transnational links as a potential threat to the Empire and monitored their development through its security services. O Malley highlights opaque aspects of the careers of popular figures from both Irish and Indian history including Subhas Chandra Bose, Jawaharlal Nehru, Eamon de Valera and Maud Gonne McBride at points when their paths crossed and also looks at how many one-time agitators went on to become international statesmen. This book encompasses aspects of Irish, Indian, British, Imperial and intelligence history and will be of interest to students, teachers and general history enthusiasts alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNationalismzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzIrelandxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadicalismzIndia. 0aRadicalismzIreland. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aBrajesh Singh.  aBritish intelligence.  aCharlotte Despard.  aEamon de Valera.  aFriends of India Society.  aIndian National Army.  aIndian independence movements.  aIndian-Irish Independence League.  aIrish Republican Army.  aIrish ationalist agitators.  aIrish political figures.  aJawaharlal Nehru.  aLeague Against Imperialism.  aMaud Gonne MacBride.  aMollie Woods.  aPhilip Vickery.  aSecond World War.  aShapurji Saklatvala.  aSubhas Chandra Bose.  aV. J. Patel.1 aO’Malley, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611843140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526118431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526118431/original  a9